cities <- read_csv(file.path("data", "largest_cities.csv"))

Joining Climate Data

In the code block below, use the left_join function to combine the cities data set with the koppen metadata. Note that the key has a different name in each of the two data sets.

cities %>%
  left_join(koppen, by = c("koppen_code" = "code"))

Take a close look at the data set you created in the last question. Scrolling all the way to the final columns, you should see the name of the climate region and the default color added into the data set.

Something, however, has happened to the first variable in the combined data set. What is the (new) name of the first variable in the combined output? Answer: name.x

It turns out that both the cities data set and the koppen dataset both contain a variable named “name”. In R, a data set cannot contain two columns with the same names. By default, left_join adds a suffix to distinguish variables that came from the first data set and those that came from the second dataset. I generally find the default suffix values to not be ideal because they change both the names in the left table (the one that contains the observations of interest) as well as the the new metadata columns. Let’s see how to change these suffix values.

The left_join function has an optional argument called suffix. You can supply two string values to it to describe what suffix values are placed on the first and second tables in the join. The default value is c(".x", ".y"). I typically find something with the first entry empty to be more practical. So, for example: c("", "_koppen"). In the code below, repeat the left join with this suffix option:

cities %>%
  left_join(koppen, by = c("koppen_code" = "code"), suffix = c("", "_koppen"))
## # A tibble: 81 × 28

Verify that the variable names match what you expected to find in the new data set. The same suffix option can be used to modify the output for other table joins.

Below, pipe the joined data set from the last question into a scatterplot with longitude on the x-axis and latitude on the y-axis. Color the points based on the default Köppen codes using an identity color scale:

cities %>%
  left_join(koppen, by = c("koppen_code" = "code"), suffix = c("", "_koppen")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = color)) +
    scale_color_identity()

Manual colors with a legend

There is one problem with the plot that we created to color the cities by their Köppen codes. There’s no legend for the plot. A way to rectify this problem is to color the points using the variable name_koppen and use the colors in the koppen metadata table to describe a manual scale with scale_color_manual. Specifically, we need:

scale_color_manual(values = koppen$color, labels = koppen$name).

Below, redo your plot with this color value and scale.

cities %>%
  left_join(koppen, by = c("koppen_code" = "code"), suffix = c("", "_koppen")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = color)) +
    scale_color_manual(values = koppen$color, labels = koppen$name)

The plot should like nice, but does requires a wide screen to see all of the colors given the long descriptions in the legend.

Creating join table

Sometimes it can be useful to create a small metadata table directly in R using the tibble function. This can than be used to more easily do mutating or filtering of a dataset. We will practice this by looking at the continents in the cities dataset. To start, compute the unique values of the continent variable in the dataset (there are many different ways to do this):

cities %>%
  group_by(continent) %>%
  summarize()
## # A tibble: 5 × 1
##   continent    
##   <chr>        
## 1 Africa       
## 2 Asia         
## 3 Europe       
## 4 North America
## 5 South America

Here are the continent names in French:

  • Asie, Amérique du Sud, Amérique du Nord, Afrique, Europe)

In the next question, use the mutate function to create a new variable called continent_fr in the cities data that gives the continent names in French. Pipe this to a plot with longitude on the x-axis, latitude on the y-axis, and the points colored to the name of the continent in French:

cities %>%
  mutate(continent_fr = "default") %>%
  mutate(continent_fr = if_else(continent == "Asia", "Asie", continent_fr)) %>%
  mutate(continent_fr = if_else(continent == "South America", "Amérique du Sud", continent_fr)) %>%
  mutate(continent_fr = if_else(continent == "North America", "Amérique du Nord", continent_fr)) %>%
  mutate(continent_fr = if_else(continent == "Africa", "Afrique", continent_fr)) %>%
  mutate(continent_fr = if_else(continent == "Europe", "Europe", continent_fr)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = continent_fr))

Next, create a data set using the tibble() function and save the data set as a variable called continent_names. The data will contains one row for each continent and should have two variables: continent and continent_fr. This gives a mapping between the English and French names.

continent_names <- tibble(
  continent = c("Asia", "South America", "North America", "Africa", "Europe"),
  continent_fr = c("Asie", "Amérique du Sud", "Amérique du Nord", "Afrique", "Europe")
)

continent_names
## # A tibble: 5 × 2
##   continent     continent_fr    
##   <chr>         <chr>           
## 1 Asia          Asie            
## 2 South America Amérique du Sud 
## 3 North America Amérique du Nord
## 4 Africa        Afrique         
## 5 Europe        Europe

In the code below, join the cities dataset with the continent_names dataset. Pipe the data into a plot with longitude on the x-axis and latitude on the y-axis, coloring the points with the variable continent_fr.

cities %>%
  left_join(continent_names, by = "continent") %>%
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = continent_fr))

The plot should now show the legend in French. In the code below, recreate the plot but add better labels for the x-axis, y-axis, and legend. Add a short title.

cities %>%
  left_join(continent_names, by = "continent") %>%
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = continent_fr)) +
    labs(x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude", color = "Continent",
         title = "World Cities by Continent")

Semi_join: an example

We have learned about the verb slice. There is another variation called slice_sample that takes a random subset of the data. It takes a named argument called n that tells us how many rows to randomly select from the data. In the block below, randomly select five rows from the cities dataset (run the code a few times to verify that the results change):

cities %>%
  slice_sample(n = 5)

We are going to do something slightly different that requires the use of a filtering join. We want to pick 5 randomly selected countries from the data set and then return all of the cities that are within those countries. The sampling should not be weighted by the number of cities within each countries that are in our data set.

To start, create a table called selected_countries that has a single column called country and five rows that have been selected from the countries in the cities data. Make sure that you are not over-weighting based on the number of cities (so China should be just as likely as Angola to be selected).

selected_countries <- cities %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
  summarize() %>%
  slice_sample(n = 5)

selected_countries
## # A tibble: 5 × 1
##   country       
##   <chr>         
## 1 Malaysia      
## 2 Brazil        
## 3 Egypt         
## 4 Sudan         
## 5 United Kingdom

Now, use a semi-join to select all of the cities that are in these countries from the cities data set. Pipe the selected cities into a scatter plot with longitude on the x-axis, latitude on the y-axis, and the points colored by country.

cities %>%
  semi_join(selected_countries, by = "country") %>%
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = country))

While a bit artificial, this is a good example of how and why you might use filtering joins.
